mission from previously established Space Access / Launch program elements within the Assured Access to Space (AATS) portfolio e.g. National Security Space
Launch (Space) - EMD (PE 1206853SF) which enable RDT&E in support of spacelift activities within the AATS portfolio.
Project 640016's name was changed to On-Orbit Servicing, Mobility, and Logistics (SML). Prior years' funding for On-Orbit Servicing, Mobility & Logistics was executed
within PE 1206853SF (i.e., 16.9M in FY2022 and 30.0M in FY2023, 11.5M in FY2024).
Project 646601's name was changed to Point to Point Delivery (P2D). Prior years' funding for P2D's air drop mission development was executed by AFRL related to the
Rocket Cargo Vanguard program within PE 0603032F / Future AF Integrated Technology Demos (i.e., 26.6M in FY2022, 28.9M in FY2023, 42.2M in FY2024).

A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Servicing, Mobility, and Logistics (SML) program identifies and closes space related mobility and logistics capability gaps to facilitate integration and employment
of on-orbit servicing and mobility for prepared and unprepared spacecraft and logistics in, from, and to space. The Servicing, Mobility, and Logistics mission areas
are grouped into On-Orbit SML and Point to Point Delivery (P2D). On Orbit SML includes but is not limited to on-orbit refueling, repairing, upgrading, assembling and
manufacturing; orbit repositioning; sustained maneuver; autonomous Rendezvous, Proximity Operations & Docking (RPOD); beyond geostationary orbit (XGEO)
operations. Point to Point Delivery (P2D) includes but is not limited to orbital supply prepositioning and operational downmass as well as responsive sub-orbital and
orbital point-to-point delivery operations.

 The near-term focus of the On-Orbit SML project is to establish the foundational capability areas through RDT&E, technology demonstrations, operational integration,
 and fielding of on-orbit mobility services, to include refueling. The On-Orbit SML will integrate commercially available servicing technology into operational capabilities
 including prototyping of modified commercial off the shelf (COTS) systems and services.

 The near-term focus of the P2D project will leverage technology developed within both commercial independent research and development (IRAD) and AFRL's Rocket
 Cargo Vanguard program to study and develop P2D reference missions. Advance integrated mission studies will analyze and assess military utility, technical feasibility,
 and projected technical maturation paths to develop and refine initial Point to Point Delivery (P2D) reference missions. Individual reference missions will undergo mission
 specific studies to pair emerging innovative technical commercial systems with prioritized warfighter needs to minimize research and development and non-recurring
 engineering while maximizing rapid field-ability and operational impact.


