A. Mission Description and Budget Item Justification
The Space Defense Capabilities project prototypes technologies for insertion into programs of record and provides platforms to operate prototypes in space.

 The Long Duration Propulsive Evolved Expendable Launch Vehicle Secondary Payload Adapter (abbreviated LDPE) and Rapid On-Orbit Space Technology Evaluation
 Ring (ROOSTER) provide a low-cost, rapid, and flexible on-orbit capability to host and deploy numerous prototypes and payloads in order to mature critical technologies
 and enable investment or divestment decisions. Each LDPE/ROOSTER on-orbit platform is designed to fly multiple payloads per mission, thus fully utilizing launch
 potential and providing the only recurring rideshare option for prototypes, demonstrations, and experiments to geosynchronous orbit. LDPE, consisting of the LDPE-1, -2,
 and -3A missions, concluded in FY 2024. The objectives of the ROOSTER program are to enable rapid and cost-effective technology insertion into operational programs
 of record through the on-orbit checkout and testing of prototypes, demonstrations, and experimental payloads. Additionally, ROOSTER will work to mature operational
 concepts and TTPs, such as on-obit refueling, for use within the United States Space Force (USSF) space enterprise architecture.

 Tetra provides a pathfinder to define future system architectures and operational concepts for several Space Domain Awareness (SDA) and Space Control programs
 and other mission partners, as well as prove prototype and experiment technologies for Air Force Research Laboratory (AFRL) and other DoD labs. It serves as an
 additional platform to host prototype and experiment payloads that need to operate in concert with LDPEs or ROOSTERS. As a secondary mission, it provides a training
 platform for operators to develop and demonstrate tactics, techniques, and procedures for the evolution of operations and training in alignment with objectives from
 organizations such as the National Space Test and Training Complex (NSTTC) and USSF Space Training and Readiness Command (STARCOM).

 Quasi-Zenith Satellite System-Hosted Payload (QZSS-HP) has dual goals of enhancing the US-Japan alliance and proving the feasibility and capability of a SDA sensor
 payload able to be proliferated and hosted on US and non-US satellites. In addition to prototyping such a capability, it will serve as a dedicated sensor in the Space
 Surveillance Network, enhancing SDA in Geostationary Earth Orbit (GEO) over the Eurasian theater.

 Space-to-Space (S2S) Comms (funding transferring to PE 1203609SF in FY 2026) includes development of communications technologies to synchronize space-to-
 space Command and Control (C2) and data transport needs across the space community and enable system-agnostic communication pathways via a mobile ad-hoc
 network. It enhances the Defense Advanced Research Projects Agency (DARPA) Space-Based Adaptive Communication Node (SpaceBACN) modem design to support
 long-range crosslinks and incorporate emerging optical waveform standards. In cooperation with AFRL, it develops networking systems to manage the space data
 network. It also develops and maintains a communications testbed to mature communication waveforms and validate hardware.

 In 2024, Congress added funding for GEO SmallSat communications technology.


