B. Accomplishments/Planned Programs ($ in Millions)                                                                                       FY 2024     FY 2025      FY 2026

The SMI effort is critical to competing, maturing, designing, testing, and validating a system capable of tracking emerging missile
threats outlined in the Missile Warning Missile Defense Capability Development Document (CDD).

FY 2025 Plans:
To ready Medium-Earth Orbit (MEO), Resilient Missile Warning/Missile Tracking (MW/MT) mission architecture needs for FY
2026 Epoch 1 launches and FY 2025 Epoch 2 acquisition, continue investment in Government Reference Model Based System
Engineering (MBSE) Model (GRMM), secret collateral processing Impact Level 6 (IL6) space, the Overhead Persistent Infrared
(OPIR) Modelling and Simulation Center, and invest in contractor secret intra-connectivity to the collateral space. Efforts enable
both the infrastructure and licenses required for using classified tools as well as the expertise to run the tools and models and
assess end to end system performance and operations.

Continue the development and test of Low Size Weight and Power (SWaP), high bandwidth, agile crosslinks for MEO Epoch 2
engineering designs in FY 2026 in order to bolster resilience and communication path diversity of OPIR data and import of MEO
data into enterprise networks. MEO Epoch 2 is expected to require expanded crosslink performance to pass and route tracking
and warning data for correlation and fusion in multiple locations which will benefit from crosslinks testing in laboratory test beds to
validate performance and increase the technology maturity of multiple vendor solutions.
FY 2026 Plans:
Test and demonstrate Low SWaP, high bandwidth, agile crosslinks for MEO MW/MT Epoch 2 as the FY 2026 flagship investment
for SMI Demonstrations. Deliver the necessary technical data to inform Epoch 2 of viable implementation paths, provide prototype
hardware for on-orbit demonstrations, and reduce risk to the FY 2028 launch and Initial Warfighting Capability.

Exploit early development of novel MW/MT phenomenologies to prove feasibility for cold target tracking. Transition Mid-Long
Wave Infrared sensors, Event Based Cameras, and Middle Ultraviolet sensors into integrated demonstrations with mission
partners to prove new capabilities are ready to onboard into MEO MW/MT Epoch 3. These technologies are aimed to close a
capabilities gap in traditional infrared missile tracking.

Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond
to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 increased due to emerging program requirements to deliver prototypes for on-orbit demonstrations in FY 2027-FY 2028.
