FY 2026 Plans:
As the Data Exploitation flagship investment, SMI will exploit emerging Artificial Intelligence and Machine Learning (AI/ML)
solutions to deliver tools necessary to operate the Proliferated Warfighting Architecture and manage the warfighters' cognitive
load that will be stressed by the volume of data from proliferated sensors. Develop intelligent automated ground processing and
operator Common Operating Picture (COP) solutions that ultimately put the operator on-the-loop instead of in-the-loop. More
specifically, automate target extraction, typing, and characterization with a confidence level that will enable lower priority targets
to be released and reported automatically when operators become overwhelmed, enabling operators to focus on higher priority
targets. Data exploitation will also continue to enhance methods of generating Two Dimensional (2D) monotracks and fused 3D
tracks to type and characterize Overhead Persistent Infrared (OPIR) events more precisely. In addition, data exploitation will
explore new ways to extract targets and deliver capabilities for extracting and typing targets from raw OPIR data. These efforts will
support long-term objectives of transitioning new solutions to onboard (in orbit) processing to more fully exploit proliferated sensor
investments while simultaneously mitigating challenges associated with large volumes of data overwhelming ground systems and
operators.

Data exploitation will leverage and enhance modeling and simulation tools, such as the Air Force Institute of Technology (AFIT)
Sensor and Scene Emulation Tool (ASSET) to emulate OPIR data from future proliferated sensors using high fidelity payload
models. These efforts will enable OPIR Tools, Applications, and Processing (TAP) Lab to develop and test Artificial Intelligence/
Machine Learning (AI/ML) solutions before actual sensor data becomes available.

Execute larger Development, Security, Operations (DevSecOps) infrastructure investments to include development and delivery
of a hybrid on-prem/cloud environment to fully support exploitation of projected proliferated sensor data, host associated ML
operations and provide fast access to curated data object storage for solution implementation, enabling a seamless Continuous
Integration/Continuous Delivery (CI/CD) pipeline for capability deployment to the program of record.

Rapidly respond to implement system resiliency and situational awareness necessary to operate in the contested space domain.
Activities may include, but are not limited to program office support, studies, technical analysis, experimentation, risk reduction,
prototyping, and activities that may leverage commercial, U.S. Government partnership, and international opportunities to respond
to existing and emerging adversarial threats with speed and agility.
