Title: Wide Field of View (WFOV) On-Orbit Testbed Mission Integration                                                                         -             -       18.468
Description: The flagship investment for the On-Orbit Testbed Mission Integration thrust area is the Wide Field of View (WFOV)
program. The demonstration testbed was launched on 1 July 2022 and has been a success. The system was originally
planned and budgeted for a three-year demonstration but has proven to be a valuable asset as a pathfinder for future Overhead
Persistent Infrared (OPIR) system mission integration and as a contributing sensor for the operational enterprise. WFOV is a
government owned contractor operated system with a distributed architecture that includes a Factory Reach Back Center (FRBC)
at Millennium Space Systems (MSS), a ground site at Blossom Point Tracking Facility (BPTF) and a tasking/data exploitation
site at the Boulder Ground Innovation Facility (BGIF). The system works to advance Resilient Missile Warning Missile Tracking
(MW/MT), battlespace awareness and technical intelligence in the Indo-Pacific Command (INDOPACOM) area while also pushing
the limits of OPIR utility though experimentation against targets of opportunity. This is a new major thrust but not a new start.
This effort was previously accomplished in the data exploitation thrust area and in program 1206410SF (Space Technology
Development and Prototyping).

FY 2026 Plans:
The Wide Field of View (WFOV) system proves the utility of the wide area, sensitive, persistent capability with full frame, real-
time image data provided in support of operational exercises and tests with the DoD, MDA and other targets of opportunity as
available. The WFOV program will continue to provide missile track data to support data fusion in systems that message out on
both the Theater Event System (TES) and Integrated Tactical Warning and Attack Assessment (ITW/AA) system. The program
plans to create and test new specific data products for end users as requested in support of Resilient Missile Warning Missile
Tracking (MW/MT) and Battlespace Awareness/Technical Intelligence (BA/TI) missions. The program is cooperating with the
National Geospatial-Intelligence Agency (NGA), National Air and Space Intelligence Center (NASIC) and others to make the
mono-track data and full frame messages fully accessible and available for both near real time and post processed intelligence
reporting and technical analysis. WFOV is preparing to pathfind and demonstrate the added value that Overhead Persistent
Infrared (OPIR) data could bring to several other critical mission areas and push the limits of OPIR mission capability.
FY 2025 to FY 2026 Increase/Decrease Statement:
FY 2026 Increase due to establishment of WFOV On-Orbit Testbed Mission Integration thrust area. This effort was previously
accomplished in the data exploitation thrust area.
